{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Oxalate accumulation from amino-acid catabolism is toxic and leads to acute disorders in mammals. Gut microflora are therefore pivotal in maintaining a safe intestinal oxalate balance through oxalate degradation. A number of bacteria, including Oxalobacter formigenes from the human gut, can carry out oxalate degradation via a two-step process [[cite:PUB00042988]]:</p>\r\n\r\n\n<ul><li>Formyl-CoA transferase (frc; [ec:2.8.3.16]) catalyses the transfer of the CoA moiety from formyl-CoA to oxalate.</li>\r\n<li>Oxalate decarboxylase (oxc; [ec:4.1.1.8]) catalyses the formation of formyl-CoA and carbon dioxide from oxalyl-CoA.</li></ul>\r\n\r\n<p>This entry represents the enzyme oxalyl-CoA decarboxylase ([ec:4.1.1.8]), which binds one metal ion (usually magnesium) and one thiamine pyrophosphate (TPP) per subunit as cofactors [[cite:PUB00042989]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "2q28", "name" "Crystal structure of oxalyl-coA decarboxylase from Escherichia coli in complex with adenosine-5`-diphosphate"}, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"ncbifam" {"TIGR03254" "oxalyl-CoA decarboxylase"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Oxalyl-CoA decarboxylase", "short" "Oxalyl-CoA_decarboxylase"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 11, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 354, "taxa" 1777, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 1739, "sets" 0, "proteins" 1739, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 1302}, "pathways" 3}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {"gp" {"displayName" "Genome Properties", "description" "Genome properties is an annotation system whereby functional attributes can be assigned to a genome, based on the presence of a defined set of protein signatures within that genome.", "rank" 45, "accessions" [{"accession" "GenProp0718", "url" "https://www.ebi.ac.uk/interpro/genomeproperties/genome-